Wash and dry produce.

In a small #pot{}, combine @Jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, ¾ cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

== Pickled Cucumber ==

In a medium #bowl{}, combine half the @white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later), @sugar{1/2%teaspoon} (1 tsp for 4 servings), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}.

Trim ends from @cucumber{1}. Using a #peeler{}, shave cucumber lengthwise into ribbons, rotating as you go, until you get to the seedy core; discard core. Stir ribbons into bowl with vinegar mixture.

Set aside, tossing occasionally, until ready to serve.

== Carrots ==

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add @shredded carrots{4%ounce} and cook, stirring, until just tender, ~{1%minute}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}.

== Pork Bulgogi ==

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites; cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and a pinch of salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in half the @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon} (save the rest for serving) and remaining vinegar. Cook for ~{30%seconds}, then stir in @bulgogi sauce{4%ounce}.

Bring to a simmer, then immediately turn off heat. Season with salt and pepper.

== Sriracha Crema ==

While pork cooks, in a small bowl, combine @sour cream{4%tablespoon} with @Sriracha{1%teaspoon} to taste. Stir in water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @salt{}.

== Assembly ==

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) and season with salt and pepper.

Divide rice between #bowls{}; top with pork, carrots, and pickled cucumber (draining first). Drizzle with Sriracha crema. Garnish with scallion greens and as many remaining sesame seeds as you like. Serve.

> If you can't seem to get enough of Korean-inspired flavors, bulgogi is sure to leave you satisfied. This dish centers around pork cooked in a sesame and soy sauce marinade with a little bit of peppery sweetness. But the meat is just one out of many highlights: There's also crisp quick-pickled cucumbers, tender carrots, and spicy crema, all over fluffy rice—each bowl is jam-packed and has a little bit of something for everyone.
> For 4 servings, use 1 1/2 cups water for the rice and 1 tsp sugar in the vinegar mixture. Use 2 TBSP butter in the rice instead of 1.